posts.com:
I love Television, it has this great, nocturnal feel. But if we're talking about influence, for better or worse the fact is, they were the first band to truly sound like indie rock. And true to that, they've been hugely influential on indie music. I've always been uncomfortable labeling them post-punk because while I get the desire to make a distinction between them and bands like the Ramones and the Sex Pistols, they also don't really have much to do with the harsh avant-garde experimentation of bands like Joy Division, Gang of Four, The Pop Group, Killing Joke, etc. This is something else, it's a sort of bohemian, post-Velvet Underground, Beat poet, modern art, anti-rockstar, garagey art rock. Plus they're jazzy, and Marquee Moon's title track follows the basic classical structure (build-fantasia-tag). Plus, historically they were also proto-punk - they evolved from the Neon Boys and once included Richard Hell, who literally invented punk fashion while a member. It's a kind of proto-indie rock, their closest contemporaries are other garagey, post-VU, artsy Beat poet artists like Richard Hell & The Voidoids, Patti Smith, Jim Carroll, and maybe Suicide. The safest term is probably art punk.

>>114757101
No, the post-punk bands were literally just punk bands who were artsy and avant-garde, in the first wave. Bands like Wire and Gang of Four. It's also what some punk artists evolved into, as with John Lydon moving from the Sex Pistols to Public Image Ltd. There was always an avant-garde quality to punk, and some people wanted to get more ambitious and explicit with it

posts.com:
>>114755912
Assuming we're talking about valve amps; the valves will behave/sound different depending on how hard they are pushed.
Generally
> Gain controls signal level for preamp
> Volume controls signal level for power amp
So if you turn down the volume then you aren't driving the power amp as hard, so it will sound different (in "tone" not just volume) to if you cranked it.

The output from a valve amp head is usually designed to drive a speaker load only (so 4, 8 or 16 Ohm depending on spec), DI boxes typically have a MUCH higher impedance than this (like 10k ohms).

That means that if you feed an amp head into a typical DI box you will see a huge voltage drop over the output transformer of the amp, and that can cause all kinds of bad things.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114756229
You mean power amp vs preamp? Resonance and presence affect how you have the lows and highs set in the preamp. Idk how to describe it other than set your preamp to how you like it, then when you're playing at volume use the power amp settings to dial things in for the acoustics of the room you're in.

At any rate, an attenuator can help with what you're trying to do, because part of a tube amp's dynamics and body depend on the natural break up of the tubes at different power levels. You can preserve that with an attenuator but it can still sound different than just cranking up to full volume. Probably will sound a lot better than running a 100 watt amp at a quarter to 1 on the post, for sure. It allows you to actually send some juice through your amp but then bleeds off some of that volume through an active load device, often a fan and some other circuits, then sends a signal out to the speaker. So you can get closer to full volume tone, but not at pissing off the neighbors volume. The attentuator sits between the amp line out of the amplifier, and the line in of the speaker cab.

>>114756596
The phase inverter just splits the preamp signal in two with a positive and negative signal and then each of those is amplified by the power amps because this is more energy efficient. So if there's less output from this then there's less going into the power section so you get an attenuated signal. But of course you're still not cranking the "full amp" at that point, if you want to do that then you need a load that has the same impedance characteristics as a speaker cab.

posts.com: I can vouch for the THD hot plate working well, retains character of the amp at lower volumes. They were hard to find for a while but the one guy who makes them has started back up again on reverb in past few years. I can get power tube break up on my 50W at bedroom volumes. Usually only take off 4-8 db. More aggressive attenuation can end up being hard on the power tubes. I get most of my overdrive from the preamp tubes anyway and just a little bit of breakup from the power tubes, then use attenuator to bring to reasonable level depending on situation. Really you will likely be better off getting a lower wattage amp, there are always compromises with an attenuator, although they can be useful in making too much of an amp quieter in a pinch

>then what kind of scale has maj7 or m7 chords in it?
7th chords are just a triad (root, third and fifth) plus a 7th added. A C major 7th chord would be a C, E, G, and a B added, a C minor 7th chord would be a C, Eb, G, and a B added. So 7th chords are still part of the major/minor scales.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>114738232
The resolution, as in sample rate and or bit depth? You can't do that from the sampler alone, but you can set up the sampler with a rate crusher like Distructor in Patcher. Then, you can modulate the sample rate based on note velocity, or an lfo, or randomize it.

So yes, you can do that.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>114738347
Mhm, you mean that it sometimes only plays 8th notes I guess. The answer is yes, but you can't do it from the sequencer alone. One way I can think of doing this is routing an lfo to the amplitude knob in the sampler(this doesn't affect notes already played), and having the lfo go to zero between 8th notes. Then you can set up the lfo so it triggers when you want it to.

You can do it, but not simply. I guess you can make a Patcher module with macro controls too make it easy, but the set-up is still complex.

you did good on volume but your low end is too muffled and not tight. Check the mid side to make sure the side is gone by at least 150 hz for both the kick and bass. Then check to make sure the bass sub frequencies ramp down, left to right in terms of loudness. If the middle sub frequency is higher than the left-most sub frequency on the eq, then itll make it sound muffled

posts.com:
I think the most NPC behavior I find IRL is people who exalt the genius of some popular band without actually knowing much about the music, at the expense of everything else. It's closely tied to the Dunning-Kruger effect. I remember once at a party we were playing the Germs, and this guy started whining that it was really shitty rock with bad teen notebook poetry or something like that. I asked him what music he liked, and he started lecturing me about how the greatest song ever written was Iris by the Goo Goo Dolls. I wish I'd shown him the Goo Goo Dolls' early Replacements rip off period lol

In another example, when I was about 16 I was hanging out with a couple 23 year olds, and this guy was being really weird and autistic about how amazing Radiohead was. Radiohead is an amazing band, but it didn't really seem like he knew them in depth, being a Radiohead fan was just superficially part of his identity. The other band he thought was as genius as Radiohead was Panic! At the Disco.

It's the pretension that's the problem, not the artist. I have a friend whose favorite artists are Taylor Swift and Third Eye Blind, but he isn't at all pretentious about it and he's very open-minded. It's just that he likes pop music. IMO there's nothing NPC about that.

posts.com:
I am OBSESSED with Wagner's operas. The medievalist visions they inspire in my mind are like nothing else. I see armored knights charging into battle, fair maidens in flowing dresses, and dragons breathing fire. It's like Game of Thrones, but with even better music (sorry, Ramin Djawadi).

Every time I listen to "Ride of the Valkyries," I imagine myself soaring through the skies on the back of a giant eagle (or maybe a dragon, if I'm feeling particularly epic). And don't even get me started on "The Flying Dutchman" - the ghost ship and the doomed love story give me chills every time.

But it's not just the grand, epic stories that have me hooked. The emotional depth of the characters is unparalleled. I have never related more to a fictional character than I do to Tristan in "Tristan and Isolde." That longing, that unquenchable desire for something just out of reach - it's like Wagner is speaking directly to my soul.

>>114729358
I hated Bach for a long time. I was obsessed with Beethoven.

But then I started playing the inventions and sinfonias. Then I started playing the Well Tempered Clavier. That kept me occupied for several years. In that time I also started listening to the B Minor Mass and the Brandenburg concertos.

Then I played the English and French Suites and now I bounce around between all of his works. I never got anywhere close to a professional musician, but I played enough Chopin, Beethoven, Mozart, Haydn and so on to have an appreciation for the music.

The thing about Bach is this: this guy didn't write music like anybody else. He didn't write music, he didn't write philosophy - he wrote scripture.

When I play his music the qualities that stand out to me above all else are his integrity and devotion. He is, in my mind, the perfect combination of academic and artist; of craftsman and theoretician.

His forms are not just "good" - they are perfect. He can be lighter than air, and more dense than gold. When he states the subject, he means it, and he uses it with integrity. He is the first artist that made me question, "What is music, really? Is this sound, or a proof?" His fugues are iron-wrought. His harmonic vocabulary second to none.

I can understand why his music inspires the devotion it does over the centuries. But then you contrast this absurd combination of poetic-scientist with Bach the man and it gets even more interesting.

Sex-obsessed (evidently, by his number of children), beer-obsessed, coffee-obsessed, quick to fight and confront, and living within a small area of Germany for his entire life, without apparent care for the world outside of Lutheranism, and without really appreciation from the world. Bach was not appreciated in his time.

He is hard to appreciate. I think Bach is the musician's musician. He's become something of a virtue signal among musicians. But that signal exists for a reason.

posts.com:
The music on the classic Marquee Moon lies somewhere between art rock, punk, new wave, and almost progressive rock at points to create something original and unique. In fact, the work that Television developed with Marquee Moon is incredible above all for the ability to look ahead, to push the boundaries musically. Of all that, Verlaine's group threw away nothing, proving to be both a masterpiece of synthesis and foresight. It's a sound that very few other bands managed to capture.

The piece that best formalizes these heterogeneous blends of genres is naturally the title track, not only perhaps the most beautiful piece in the history of what is considered "punk" in the broadest sense (and it takes some liberties with the definition of punk, as its almost more post punk before post punk) but also a milestone and putative father of that cauldron that would later be organized in the form of the "alternative" genres of rock (in the even further side). If Marquee Moon (the record) has rightly been defined as one of the definitive albums of this century for the sound of the guitar, then its title track is the best example of why. Torn Curtain is the other extended piece on the disc and follows in the footsteps of that masterpiece, offering the most baroque of Verlaine's guitar performances. Verlaine's poetic sensibilities as a lyricist and his jazzy, Jeff Beck-influenced approach to soloing are instantly noticeable. I have never heard a guitarist come as close to imitating the sound of John Coltrane's saxophone as Verlaine (with the possible exception of Sonny Sharrock).

>Marquee Moon has frequently appeared on rankings of the greatest albums of all time.[68] The Guardian and Melody Maker placed it 33rd and 25th, respectively, on lists published at the turn of the 21st century.[69] In Larkin's 2000 book All Time Top 1000 Albums, Marquee Moon ranked at number 53.[70] On September 23, 2003, the album was reissued by Rhino Entertainment with several bonus tracks, including the first CD appearance of Television's 1975 debut single "Little Johnny Jewel (Parts 1 & 2)".[71] That same year, it was named the fourth-greatest album of all time by NME, while Rolling Stone placed it at number 128 on its list of the 500 greatest albums of all time.[72][nb 1] It has been viewed as one of the greatest rock albums ever by English radio DJs Marc Riley, who said that "there's been nothing like it before or since", and Mark Radcliffe, who called it "the nearest rock record to a string quartet—everybody's got a part, and it works brilliantly."[74] Based on such listings, the aggregate website Acclaimed Music ranks Marquee Moon as the 28th most acclaimed album in history.[68]

posts.com:
>>114758640
You can only do so far until you are not longer in touch with the youth and you stop being 'it'
Once you form your sound (confined from what you though was cool in your teens) and you develop it for a decade of revelancy, it's just natural to just don't get what kids like now or simply refusing get a whole makeover of your music to appeal to kids again (as a mid 30's something)

At that point, when you got a sound for a decade you only have two options

A)accept that you are not the hottest thing anymore and go on with your own style, keep pushing it forward and MAYBE if you do it right you hit a second phase of relevancy, be it with the youth (think Arctic Monkeys now) or with music fans (think swans)
Or B
B) Keep (most of the time sadly) chasing the new fad or sound that you clearly don't get anymore (think 90's Kiss) and hope for a miracle that might or not happen, thinking you are gonna outsmart the insticts of cool teenagers that you yourself didn't get fooled on and that are the same fucking reason you are in that position right now. Think of the endless crap that just doesn't age well no matter what they do


American Idiot Green Day and David Bowie seem to be two exceptions or combinations of those rules, but they are a few of the outliers or lucky ones.

Green Day is an especially interesting one, cause when they released they second wave they went from failure to failure to commercial success from a strike of god or whatever to FAILURE AGAIN
You might say that Bowie had a lot of misses but he made chasing a sound his gimmick, Green Day was a combination of skill and luck, and see where they are now again

You can't play three chord rock forever, your sound has to evolve with you and you gotta accept you don't have it anymore >>114756066

posts.com:
I can see his point and why he'd say that. I love MBV, but I honestly like Suede even more. Really, I'd say Blair took advantage of Britpop, using it as a vehicle to appeal to the youth by associating himself with Oasis and Blur. Blair used them as a tool, and after they were associated with him, he benefitted from their success, so yeah, they and "Cool Britannia" were probably pushed by him. It made sense - journalists pushed a sort of jingoism and patriotic pride with Britpop, which the bands themselves rarely identified with. Shields was the opposite - he was a thoroughly underground Irish guitarist who was into post-punk and noise rock, and was into bands like Sonic Youth and Dinosaur Jr. A band like Oasis probably seemed ridiculous and grotesque to him, with all their rockstar cliches, the same way Kurt Cobain had contempt for Guns N' Roses with all their rockstar posturing.

But Britpop has a lot of great, frankly anti-establishment music. Suede were about as challenging and intellectual as a pop band could be, Pulp were basically cynical social critics, James were a holdover from the Smiths era, none had much tolerance for the British media.

posts.com:
I think there are different kinds of loners. On the one hand, you have people who truly prefer to be alone - in an extreme clinical sense, people with schizoid personality disorder. They don't feel a desire for relationships. They wouldn't play sad, longing music, because they don't feel sad or lonely about being alone.

Then there are people who have difficulty forging relationships. This could be for a clinical reason, like depressed people, people with avoidant personality disorder, or some people with autism spectrum disorder who struggle socially (though at this point I've met some very social, charismatic autists, so it's complicated), or people who are socially marginalized. This is the group I'm most sympathetic to.

Then there are people who burned their bridges and are filled with regret.

I scrolled through various "music review" searches grabbing some thumbnails that I thought were better than most of the others. The thumbnails stand out, the text is easy to read on them and directly relevant to the content of the video without bloat, there isn't too much or too little information. a couple have edited in examples of the videos content, that can be good. the ones that don't have a gripping expression being made by a person or character. all four do, though you can definitely get away with not having a persons face in a thumbnail. I don't use faces.

I don't know anything about any of those videos by the way, I don't watch music reviews. I think one might even be a cartoon review. I mostly watch history stuff on youtube, look up "dan davis history" if you want to see an example of what I consider to be 11/10 thumbnails. pretty much all of his are finely crafted.

when it comes to the algorithm, you want your titles to be grabbing while matching as close as possible the most likely things people are going to type into the search bar that could bring them to your video. use all variations of keywords in the title and description, even if there is a bit of redundancy. add tags if there is too much redundancy in the title/description. it helps to start typing in some stuff in the search bar related to your video and see what autocompletes.

also, focus on what is in demand. look for what is lacking among other content creators and provide it. look for what is fresh and come out with the content before others do. if there is a new release, jump on it. if there is something that doesn't get talked about enough, say so and make a video about it.

posts.com:
Personally, I have to say that I never had much time for King Crimson. I disliked their first album and, apart from a track here and there, didn't find much I cared for on later albums either. To make things harder, they were contemporaries of Henry Cow and we were often pointlessly compared with them (especially Fred Frith who got foolishly compared/confused with Robert Fripp). But we never saw the connection really; they were working in a much narrower musical field than we were. And when they began to make big statements about their originality for improvising (around Jaimie Muir/Larks Tongues time) we found that frankly rather pathetic. But that was their way - after all Fripp claimed to have invented 'frippertronics', which is either a mark of ignorance on his part or outrageous arrogance, since every guitarist 'invented' that obvious procedure. I was not a fan of the other groups you list either, or Yes or Genesis for that matter, the quintessential 'progressive' groups. I don't think we had much in common with any of them. We certainly didn't learn anything from them. I, for instance, would have to go back to early Zappa, Beefheart, Barrett's Pink Floyd, Soft Machine, AMM, Sun Ra, Coltrane, Coleman, Stockhausen, Schoenberg and so on for influences. And for contemporary bands in the 70's, Magma, Faust, Samla Mammas Manna.

-Chris Cutler

>>114757583
dude
see if you can understand this when it's broken down in simple terms
humans can hear a limited frequency range, nominally ~20 kHz for young people, probably around 16-18 kHz for most adults, with the upper limit being around 25 kHz
a bandlimited signal can be perfectly reconstructed if the sample rate is more than twice the bandwidth
since ideal brickwall filters don't exist, loosen the constraints a little bit with a slightly higher sample rate and a slightly less steep filter
a signal can be bandlimited, discretized and reconstructed without any audible change to the sound

further...
discretization of amplitude adds noise to the signal
if this is done correctly, it's pushed out of the audible range (noise shaping)
the noise that's added is quite small, certainly less than the background noise level of a tape recorder or a mixing console, or probably even a mic preamp

also, an electrical signal is AN IMITATION of an acoustic sound, and an arrangement of magnetic domains on a piece of tape or a wiggly scratch in PVC is AN IMITATION of that signal. these things (the microphone, speaker, tape recorder, or turntable) fuck up the sound many orders of magnitude more than an ADC/DAC

>>114757161
the problem with the "thrash metal" label, is that really has nothing to do with "classic" thrash metal. The bands that came up later in the 80's basically took the key elements of what made Metallica and Slayer stand out and boiled them down to produce, for better or worse, a formulaic type of metal that eventually became known as thrash. Exodus can be considered the first Thrash Metal band because in '85 were already playing something much more similiar to canonical thrash than what Metallica or Megadeth ever did. Slayer (and sometimes Anthrax) is the only band in the big 4 that actually uses skank beat as a core element of their sound yet when you think of thrash you immediately think of "tupa-tupa".
Metallica just evolved their sound regardless of the metal scene and eventually matured out of just "thrashing", Megadeth did too, albeit in a different direction.
The reason why Metallica feel different is because they simply are, they never cared about fitting in and it eventually payed out.

I've been in thrash bands for more than 15 years now and despite loving the genre, the fandom is tone of the most obnoxious in metal. Thrashers really think their dumb culture of MOSH! beer and aliens is something that has to be taken very serious.

No. Stereolab did something completely different and Broadcast did something completely different. They both made important and brilliant music, and neither was or will ever be rendered obsolete by either or anything else. Stereolab included influences from noise pop, lounge, bossa nova, krautrock and art pop together while Broadcast took influences from psychedelic pop, folk, library music, hauntology, sound collage etc. No need to tear one down to appreciate another

>>114758329
If you're interested, James has a side project called Children of Alice. It's an experimental project that is essentially what a future Broadcast album would've been like. There's also Seeland which is made up of the former Broadcast guys. In general, if you want more of the later Broadcast feeling, check out The Focus Group and basically the entire Ghost Box catalogue. Also Vanishing Twin is (really really good) Broadcast, Pram amd Stereolab worship for a new-ish band

posts.com: For a band that was hardly known when it was changing the course of rock music, it was surprising that its reunion caused so much sensation. Their first album in two decades, MBV, was heralded as a masterpiece by pretty much all the publications that had ignored their real masterpieces. Truth is that the beginning borders on self-parody: She Found Now (basically an update of Sometimes) whispers lounge pop to an endlessly repetitive guitar pattern; the amateurish shoegaze-pop of Only Tomorrow has an unfinished guitar progression that the average hard-rock band would have turned into dynamite; and Who Sees You (basically an update of Only Shallow) boasts one of the most predictable guitar solos of the genre. If nothing else, the second trio of songs drops Shields' annoying whisper for Bilinda Butcher's coldly morbid hissing. However, the suspenseful and futuristic cosmic quasi-instrumental Is This And Yes is hardly innovative 20 years after Stereolab; and If I Am is little more than a nostalgic tribute to the film music of the 1960s. New You is a winner, relatively speaking, of what used to be called "bubblegum pop": a marching progression a` la Tommy Roe's Dizzy, a guitar vibrato a` la Tommy James' Crimson & Clover, etc. This Freudian return to the (rock) womb continues on the chaotic imitation of the Madchester sound of the 1990s of In Another Way. The album closes with the two "experimental" pieces. Other than looping a frenzied drum pattern, it is not clear what the instrumental Nothing Is is trying to achieve. Wonder 2 is hyper-distorted warped psychedelia and does certainly more than simply update Loveless to the 21st century. However, the problem remains the same: a trivial idea gets repeated endlessly without coalescing into anything of substance.
